{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778525877,"nonce":"acKSAzayF9NVD5smYImWMndA5iI=","message":"**Resolution of variance-metric mismatch (comment #16) — option 2 adopted.**\n\nComment #16 surfaced a methodological mismatch: the 6-cell matrix (`2bc95fd`) used CV (SD/mean of peak vel) while the prior `baseline_jerk_vrnn_matrix` used pairwise profile-RMSE ratio. Three options were identified.\n\n**Chosen resolution: Option 2** — adopt pairwise profile-RMSE ratio (within-cell / nearest-across-cell) as the canonical replicate-variance metric. CV is retained as an auxiliary summary but does not drive decisions.\n\n**Recomputed 6-cell results with RMSE ratio (primary):**\n\n| Cell | Vel-RMSE ratio | Beats threshold (\u003c 0.50)? |\n|------|---------------|---------------------------|\n| gru__jerk | 1.129 | No |\n| gru__jerk_motor_pre | 0.461 | Yes |\n| gru__jerk_smooth_high | 0.037 | Yes |\n| gru__jerk_motor_smooth_combo | 0.036 | Yes |\n| gru__jerk_loss_v_terminal | 0.882 | No |\n| gru__jerk_loss_historical | 1.131 | No |\n\n3/6 cells beat the threshold. Prior 'all 6 passed' claim was artefact of CV vs RMSE-ratio mismatch.\n\nThe `analyse_anti_anticipation_6cell_variance.py` script now computes RMSE ratios as the primary output. `scripts/diagnose_combo_hold_motor.py` added as a companion diagnostic. Updated `results/2bc95fd/notes/variance_analysis.md` with RMSE-primary table + RMSE detail rows.\n\nCross-ref: `2bc95fd` (corrective comment posted there too). Script changes on `feature/rmse-recompute-and-audit`.","files":null}]}